work_exp:
[u"Senior IDM Engineer
Baylor Scott and White Health - Dallas, TX
September 2013 to January 2016
While employed at Baylor Scott and White Health, I had the opportunity to work with some amazing people and technology. I stepped into a role there that was the lead architect on various projects from day one, and in that role until I left the organization. Following is a list of some of the projects and accomplishments, both the team and myself, were presented with throughout my time with them.

In addition to the major projects listed below, here are a few highlights that were outside the scope of those projects:

• Designed and deployed four new SDLC environments to replace the existing environments as their configuration drift was too great due to lack of maintenance over the years. The design included full architectural specifications as well as environmental governance classifications and definitions.
• Designed and deployed a integration system to provide build automation, better source code entry point into the build process, build artifact management, automated hooks for testing, and overall, better control of the software development lifecycle.
• Started to generate standard containers and container templates for deploying new instances of existing applications, as well as new applications whose resource profile allowed. The container technologies implemented within the various environments consisted of Docker and LXC containers.
• Deployed Vagrant to provide customized systems for development purposes. This allowed for faster turn around and benefited the team during times when there was a high priority build or integration that needed to be produced.
• Once we had SailPoint fully deployed, we moved from the ant-based build system to a maven-based system. After that had settled, we then migrated to Gradle and standardized on that platform as the core build system for the overall integration pipeline and system.
Sun Identity Management Platform Optimization and Maintenance:
My first individual responsibility was to assume the role of application owner to the Sun Identity Manager system. This include the core system as well as ownership of all interfaces to all downstream and/or connected systems and applications. Following is a list of some of the subprojects that were completed as part of general maintenance or adding new functionality to the application.

• Designed and implemented a pull-based mechanism for data feed processing from the identity authoritative source within Sun Identity Manager. This consisted of two python frameworks and standard system shell scripts to accomplish.

• Restructured the codebase within the main processing forms for the authoritative identity source within Sun Identity Manager to consolidate the number of calls to various scripts and libraries. The
net result was a more streamlined form allowing for faster processing of each record in the source
feed.

• Analyzed and redesigned a significant number of the existing workflows to improve the performance of provisioning and de-provisioning as well as allow for greater flexibility in regards to event scheduling and such.

• Redesigned the public facing component of Sun Identity Manager so that there was no externally exposed area of the architecture. This allowed for simpler access policies(PnP policies) as well as easier overall administration and maintenance.

• Designed and implemented a migration plan for moving Sun Identity Manager 7.0 running on a 32-bit JVM over to a 64-bit JVM. The JVM used was Oracle-based. This allowed for more optimized Java configuration parameters to be passed by the application to the JVM at application initialization.

• Supported and maintained the enterprise source code repository for the Sun Identity Manager application. This included all development branches for all of the custom functionalities implemented(as well as not) within the application.

Virtual Directory Service Deployment
Lightweight Directory Services Deployment
Ater the merger between Baylor and Scott and White Health was complete, we starte the design phase for a virtual directory service to allow for better flexibility as resources began to transfer and migrate between the various business units.

• Implemented AD LDS in DMZ to allow vendor applications to be able to generate necessary profile information within their application from the data that was exposed within the AD LDS implementation. This was later replaced by a Radiant Logic enterprise solution.

Virtual Directory Service Deployment
This was really the second phase of the Lightweight Directory Services deployment project. Where that project began, the Virtual Directory Service deployment project finalized and streamlined the overall system in a way that made it accessible to virtually any enterprise application that had a need to utilize some type of data view that VDS could present.

Enterprise Migration From OpenSSO to SecureAuth
Worked with application owners as well as various business units and partners to coordinate the migration of existing service providers controlled by OpenSSO, over to the new SecureAuth platform. We were able to do this in a way that had zero downtime and provided better functionality and performance than the previous system.

• The most challenging piece to this was decoupling OpenSSO from Sun Identity Manager as it was running as the Access Manager role. This required and exhaustive code review of all actively deployed code to ensure that there would be no negative impact once we split the two systems. The project was a complete success.

Identity Management Redeployment Project (SailPoint IdentityIQ)
The Idenitty Management Redeployment(IDMR) project was really the project that I was queried on during the interview process prior to starting employment with BSWH. It was already well known that the Sun Identity Manager system need to be replaced as it had reached end-of-life two years prior.

After the successful go-live of phase one for central Texas, I was one of the three people on the original team to be recipients of Baylor's Service Excellence Award for exceptional performance during that stage of the project.

• Worked as part of a project team that generated criteria for a formal RFP process that was approved by senior leadership. The process leading up to the final draft involved collaboration with stakeholders and various business units and interested parties. The final draft of this process was executed and led to the selection of the new solution that would be implemented.

• Worked as part of a project team that coordinated with our business partner, as well as internal
stakeholders, to design and develop a project plan to replace the Sun Identity Manager implementation with a new IdentityIQ solution from SailPoint.

• Designed and implemented the infrastructure architecture component of the IdentityIQ deployment
project. This encompassed three environments at first and was later expanded to four with a fifth
being considered.

• Worked with the project team to assist in designing the overall application layer logic for the initial
rollout of the IdentityIQ application. This was a very detailed and highly envolved process that involved all stakeholders and touched almost every aspect of the business.

• Worked with the project team as well as with our business partner to development and implement the various components necessary to support the application architecture that was approved. This involved the creation of rules, rule libraries, workflows, etc as well as the necessary application and
connected system interfaces as depicted within the overall architecture.

• Personally wrote the code for many of the core functiona libraries in IdentityIQ. The included the core codebase for the joiner process, leaver process, mover process(aka, change manger), leave of absence, immediate termination, and more. We worked very closely with our business partner and SailPoint implementation services during this types of sprints.

• Designed an initial role hierarchy for role-based access control that was later expanded upon while working with the project team and various other resources that were brought in for peer and other
types of design review.

• Designed and deployed the initial configuration and schema for the various application interfaces within the IdentityIQ application deployment for phase one of the project.

• Coordinated with database management team to implement the IdentityIQ repository database. This was an Oracle 11G R2 database running on AIX. There were three initial databases, one for each of our SDLC environments, and was later expanded to include a fourth database to service a specialized data mining environment.", u'Systems Architect

Bonneville Power Administration - Portland, OR
June 2011 to February 2013
Main responsibilities are centered around developing custom super computing solutions on both x86 and SPARC based platforms utilizing Solaris 10, and various distributions of Linux.
Directory Services Architectural Redesign and Deployment
Project Consisted of 3 Phases:
• Planning Phase
• Implementation Phase
• Maintenance Phase
Component Details:
I was responsible for designing a Active Directory architecture that implemented many of the newer generation, and advanced functions found within the current ADS offerings. these were as follows:
Active Directory Domain Services (AD DS, deployed by default)
The AD DS deployment within BPA was where to core of the Active Directory Modernization project payload was delivered. Substantial work was done to optimize the following:

• Both intra-site and inter-site replication optimization
• DFS-R implementation and migration of sysvol
• DNS Application partition migration and optimization
• DNS Zone implementation and consolidation
• DNS Global Namespace implementation
• FIM design and implementation to assist with workflow and identity management.
Active Directory Federation Services 2.0 (AD FS)
AD FS was deployed to help provide extranet SSO and implement claims-based authentication for various internal development initiatives.
Active Directory Lightweight Directory Services (AD LDS)
The purpose of deploying AD LDS within the environments at BPA were threefold:

• To strengthen the security posture of their existing extranet, as well as to help consolidate identity management in that environment as well.
• To provide an integration point for non-Microsoft-based systems that allowed them to communicate back to the primary directory service, thus consolidating multiple authentication stores into one.
• To provide identity management for Oracle based systems that resided in the middle tier. This was primarily for applications such as PeopleSoft, Asset Suite, Sunflower, etc

In addition to the items mentioned, another(if not obvious) benefit was integration of POSIX systems with Microsoft Active Directory Services in regards to providing a central authentication store that was/is consistent across the entire agency
Active Directory Certification Services (AD CS)
AD CS was deployed in a three-tier architecture to provide core PKI services to the internal divisions of BPA.
All aspects of this implementation had to comply with numerous federal regulations as the first two tiers, and all root CAs were cross-signed by the Federal DOE PKI and tied back in to one of the Federal PKI bridge that the DOE is anchored too.
All system builds associated with this section of the project were STIG compliant. The STIGs used for this were NSA and DISA.

Another item to mention here is that the design took into account dependencies outside of the project and design to those as "soft requirements" as the project allowed. The end result of this added effort, was faster "time to market" for the exchange deployment team, the respect that much of the site replication calculations and design work was already done for them and required very little if no change at all.

Exadata Infrastructure Design and Deployment
For this project, I designed the management environment, as well as all of the infrastructure elements leading up to the demarcation point between the prod environment, and the database machines internals. I also worked with the various business units as well as the database design team to generate the overall Exadata capacity plan and overall architecture. In the end, we went with the following configuration:

• 1 Exadata release 2 Full Rack
• 2 Exadata release 2 Half Racks
• 2 Exadata release 2 Quarter Racks
Duties and Duties and Responsibilities
• Maintain Exadata Machine, including patching, database nodes, storage cells, hardware components and infini bandswitches
• Executed project management, technical lead and liaison responsibilities between business user and technical group
• Install Oracle 11g Enterprise Grid Control and Oracle Web Logic server, configure multiple RAC, stand-alone and standby Oracle databases, and install Exadata Plug-in to monitor Exadata Storage cells in Grid Control
• Move Oracle Database Server Farm from Sacramento, CA to Las Vegas, NV data center
• Created and implemented load balancer for performance and fail over utilization
• Setup Oracle 10g Grid Control Management Server, installing and capturing Oracle databases on Sun Solaris 10 servers
• Planned and implemented Disaster Recovery site for Oracle databases in Las Vegas using Oracle Data Guard, creating standby logical databases for real-time data replication
• Assisted database administration team in the conversion and replacement of custom backup/recovery Unix scripts to RMAN
• Recommended standards and procedures for development, deployment, version control, source code management, change control process and capacity planning functions, suggesting tools to eliminate 40-50% of development time
• Provided innovative strategies for better database administration, maintenance, tuning and backup
Environment:
• 1 Exadata (Release 2) Full Rack. Database Machine
• 2 Exadata (Release 2) 2 Half Racks. Database Machines
• 2 Exadata (Release 2) 2 Quarter Racks. Database Machines
• Oracle VM Server
• Oracle VM Server for SPARC
• Oracle 11g Rel2
• Oracle 11g Grid Control
• Oracle RMAN
• Oracle ASM
• Oracle RAC
• OEL 6
• OEL 5
• Solaris 11
• Solaris 10

Oracle Middle Tier Upgrade and New Architectural Implementation
This project really was, for all intents and purposes, part of the Exadata deployment, but needed to be called out separately for a number of internal factors.
The design that we went with in the end was an architecture that leverages Oracles virtualization technologies to side step a licensing issue with one of the applications that essentially locks they OS at Solaris 10, until they upgrade their code base. Not wanting to live with this long term, we decided to virtualize Solaris 10, on top of Solaris 11 via Oracle VM Server for SPARC where necessary while still allowing us to standardize on Solaris 11 moving forward.
Application Stack Design Criteria
• Oracle PeopleSoft
• Ventech Asset Suite
• Sunflower Systems Asset Management
• Oracle Weblogic Server
• Microsoft Active Directory Lightweight Directory Services(as a component of the ADM project listed above) as an identity broker between the Oracle environments and the Microsoft systems.
Environment
• 4 SPARC Enterprise T4-2 Servers
• Oracle VM Server for SPARC
• Oracle VM Server
• Solaris 11 (Host Layer)
• Solaris 10 (Guest/Application Layer)

Puppet Enterprise Pre-Cloud Architecture and Deployment
I was given the opportunity to design the base architecture for the deployment of Puppet Enterprise 2.x to provide configuration management on a comprehensive level throughout the agency. I labeled this "Pre-Cloud" as this was the initial step in the direction that will ultimately lead to a full private, hybrid private cloud deployment. Other components put in place with this initiative are cfengine, Red Hat Directory Server, Oracle Enterprise Manager - Cloud Edition, Active Directory LDS, Active Directory FS 2.0, Active Directory CS, VMware View, VMware vCloud, as well as an initial test deployment of Hadoop, CloudStack, OpenStack, and others.
Platform Details
All Puppet Master and Database Servers were Red Hat Enterprise Linux v6.3
Deployed Puppet DB to provide Hierarchical data view of all managed assets
Puppet DB was a hosted MySQL instance running on a Oracle VM Server for SPARC in a RAC configuration for HA

Creation of data model to support Gas utilities, integration with several systems containing spatial and non-spatial data to create a data store to support several functions including customer support and field operations. Review of current data architecture and workflows as well as flow of data between the city and other organizations such as the county. Creation of and enterprise data architecture and proposed method of flow of data between organizations to reduce manual processes, error and data redundancy.

System Integrator, Thomas Jefferson Foundation, VA - System and Data Integration Audit
Analysis of systems across the organization containing GIS and historical artifact data to architect a unified system that will serve to present organizational and spatial data in a unified format for future application support serving internal staff and the public.

Architect and Programmer, University of Washington, WA - Facilities Management Web Application & Mobile application
Creation of a flex based web application with full editing capabilities that allows University of Washington facilities management staff to view real time information about buildings, current construction projects, project areas and change requests. The users can interact with the map to create spatial change requests which are then logged with facilities management. This application also includes 3D perspective viewing of floor data across buildings and a user and role driven security model which integrates into the University's current security system.

Architect, Anglo Platinum/Anglo American Mining, Johannesburg, South Africa - Mineral Resource Management Architecture
Conduct an investigation into operational business processes and to provide an objective view on goals for the Geospatial Project. The Geospatial Project is a project driven internally by the Mineral Resource Management (MRM) Department to provide a decision making and reporting platform within a geographical map driven context, at a mine as well as a corporate level. This architecture included a comprehensive assessment of existing software, hardware and network infrastructure, business processes, business intelligence products and recommendations on consolidating several systems across several geographically separating mining operations as well as eliminating reliance on manual tasks. This architecture created a roadmap to achieve operational integration using TOGAF methodology as well as a prototype web based business intelligence dashboard consolidating production, labour, cost and safety information across and within mining operations.

Architect and Programmer, State of New Mexico, NM - Middle Rio Grande Basin Project (MRG)
Creation of a web based mapping application that allow for staff of the State of New Mexico to monitor water usage and rights in a geographical area where water is scarce. This application integrated aerial photography, vector land use data (including historical data), plane table surveys and other data in order to determine 1) Land Use and percentages 2) Water use calculations based on land use types over several years and how that has changed 3) evaluate water rights over time 4) evaluate compliance to water rights including historical transfer of water rights and lease expiry. The application also creates comprehensive reporting on compliance in order to support the state's enforcement of water use regulations.

Architect and Programmer, Elections Nova Scotia, Canada - Poll and Electoral Boundary Redistricting Tool
Creation of a custom ArcMap desktop extension to support Elections Nova Scotia's review of polling boundaries and ultimately to support the analysis of electoral boundary review within the context of Elections Canada legal requirements for "Effective Representation". This tool creates real time information during both editing and selecting of geospatial boundaries to perform underlying geospatial analysis to display information on residential addresses, census demographic information, road information as well as other man-made, cultural and natural geographic information that would influence effective representation. This tool also provides a comprehensive audit trail for methodology when changing electoral boundaries.

Architect, City of Kitchener, Canada - Automated Vehicle Location & Salt Management System
Creation of fully functioning pilot AVL system that integrates with TachWest hardware GPS and Sensors as well as a web based dashboard mapping interface showing vehicle positions and status in real time. This information system included alerting and notification if vehicles broke certain business rules and thresholds, geofencing, comprehensive on demand reporting as well as generation of year end reports used for operational management and review. This project succeeded in replacing a previous system that relied heavily on hosted services to a completely customized in house system using best of breed software and giving the city the ability to modify reporting and display of vehicle information that is responsive to their changing business requirements.

Architect and Programmer, Geocove, FL - Damage Assessment Web Portal & Mobile field application
Creation of a flex based web portal that works with mobile field collection to provide reporting and viewing of damage assessment information collected after disasters. Self-serve report and form creation via the web portal allowing for better management of information to aid in damage recovery such as forms needed by FEMA. Mobile portion included ArcGIS Server mobile for field collection as well as iOS iPhone/iPod/iPad application for the public to download and monitor alerts, news and information regarding damage cleanup and locations of current evacuation zones.

Architect and Programmer, Timmons, VA - VizOps Common Operating Picture
Creation of second generation common operating picture to allow departments of emergency management view and interact with real time web based information that enables better responses to emergencies and disasters. Includes mobile application based on HTML 5 technology available to general public to monitor alerts and other public safety real time information.

Architect and Programmer, Power South, AL & FL - Economic Development Portal
Customization and deployment of Timmons SiteLoGIStics for PowerSouth representing all the counties of Alabama and the Florida pan handle allowing users to search for building and site information via a flex based web mapping application. Integrates detailed site and building information as well as demographic data via ESRI Business Analysis Online in order to aid site selection process.

Architect and Programmer, Sandia National Laboratory, NM - Vehicle Tracking Proof of Concept
Creation of flex based web mapping application utilizing Tracking Server in a proof of concept project for the Office of Secure Transportation. Vehicle tracking functionality included real time monitoring of vehicles entering geofences designated potential danger zone, ensuring that all vehicles within a convoy stay within set distances of each other, ensuring vehicles within a convoy do not move out of order, ensuring vehicles do not deviate from designated routes and ensuring that vehicles stay within a speed range. Any deviance from rules resulted in an alerting system.

Architect, City of Dryden - Cultural Asset Portal
Creation of hardware and software architecture to support a proposed cultural asset portal that will allow users to plan trips, view cultural assets in North Western Ontario with full multi-media integration. Includes architecture for user management system to allow for partnering agencies to manage information about cultural assets. This system also included a comprehensive user management and authentication system allowing for various levels of rights regarding the creation and updating of cultural asset information.

Architect and Programmer, Western Virginia Water Authority, VA - Web Mapping Portal
Creation of flex based web mapping site which allows users to view, query and navigate water, waste water and sewer assets. Includes water network analysis such as upstream and downstream tracing functionality and valve isolation traces.

Architect and Programmer, University of Maryland, MD - Spatial Economic Decision Support
Creation of web mapping application for cost benefit analysis and net present value calculations in order aid decision making in choosing management units to treat for invasive species in Rock Creek and Antietam. Architect and Programmer, BroadMap, VA - Broadband Mapping Portals

In addition Horizon Lab application achieves the most efficient workflow by naming tubes in the order with an accession number (i.e. a unique identifier). The applications sending orders in an HL7 message format has the capability to generate and send an accession number for tubes in the order. Proton application sending orders in an ASCII data file does not have the capability to generate and send accession numbers. Thus orders from Proton application cannot be sent directly to Horizon Lab for processing.

A solution is to develop an application called Proton Integrator to integrate orders from Proton application to Horizon Lab by receiving orders in ASCII file format, generating accession numbers and sending the order in an HL7 format on real time basis for further processing.
• Involved in code development, unit testing and handling status call every day.
• Acted as Developer & Quality Team Lead.

Project Name: Horizon Enterprise Content Manager (McKesson Corporation)

Technologies: WinForms, C#, Oracle 10g, Web Services

Role: Software Engineer

Description: This application is a Content Management system. The flow consists of storing the content with their metadata. It takes care of the proper versioning, locking & managing the contents. It intensively uses the web services & applied security. Following are the modules involved in.

♦ HECM Installation Kit - It enables user to install the heterogeneous HECM application on various platforms including Linux and windows. It can install JBOSS server with all the respective JARs and EARs. Along with this it deploys the window based HECM application for ClickOnce deployment.

♦ Submits Content - It is one of the major modules which provides user to upload contents (Data and Image file) on the server with correct metadata and version. It applies correct checksum using MD5 hash algorithm to maintain the integrity of content across the network. This whole process work on multithreaded environment.

♦ Configure security - It provide the administrator to configure Security rights, Access control List and roles. Apart from this Administrator can configure the password security policies for the different roles and users.

♦ Check-In and Check-out - This functionality provides user to Check in the content into different folders under authorized domains. It takes care of downloading the content (file) and opening it with respective editors. Along with this it allows the user to lock, delete and change the metadata of the content.

♦ Audit Reports- This module handles the Reporting Section of Project. Its major focus is on the Uploading /Downloading of Audit Reports from the server. Whenever user performs some action on the User Screen for e.g.: changing the User Password, deletion or creation of file, changing the security access etc. All these events are logged on the ActiveMQ Server using NMS. So whenever administrator wants to view the audit reports, it is downloaded from the server and displayed using Crystal Reports.

• Involved in code development, unit testing and handling status call every day.']

Prior assignment: Worked for Dow Chemical in their Houston office (May 2004 - October 2005) on various petrochemical project, in Spain, In Freeport, Texas and a
major grassroots natural gas project in Oman.', u'Architect
Bechtel National Inc - Richland, WA
July 2002 to April 2004
In Dec. 2000 the US DOE, Department of Energy Office issued a 10 year, $4
billion contract for the immobilization of millions of gallons of radioactive waste
stored at the Hanford Site in southeastern Washington State. The goal is to design and build specialized plants to convert the stored radioactive waste to solid glass, a process called vitrification. Most of the waste is currently stored in underground
tanks, some of the waste has already leaked and is contaminating groundwater.
On this project I am assigned to the Analytical Laboratory.
The Analytical Laboratory, (LAB) is a two story building, with a total enclosed
area of 85,000 sq. ft.
The LAB houses hot cells, 13 analytical radiological labs, and maintenance
shops, administrative offices and support areas. The LAB receives sampling
materials from Pretreatment Facility (PTF), High Level Waste Facility (HLW) and
Low Active Waste Vitrification Building (LAW) by way of an overhead pneumatic
auto-sampling system into a first level marshalling room.
Analysis is performed on samples received in both hot cells and radiological labs.
Process waste shall be returned to the PTF for handling and solid waste shall be
packed in storage drums and removed from WTP site for burial.

The LAB building is a two story steel frame and concrete structure. The roofing
system consist of standing seam metal panel over rigid insulation on metal roof
decking. The exterior wall system for the entire building shall be nonbearing
insulated metal sandwich panel system. The concrete mat slab for the Hot Cell
Bay, Hazardous Waste Tank Cell, and C5 Filter Room shall conform to SC-1
criteria. Marshalling Room floor system and supportive wall below at the Hot Cell
bay shall conform to SC-1 criteria.
Marshalling Room wall and roof structure shall conform to SC-2 criteria. The
remaining structure and building envelope of the LAB shall conform to SC-3
criteria. The exterior finishes for the LAB shall be similar to the other process
facilities. The entire building is pressurized (negative) with cascading
pressurization system starting with the lowest contamination areas ending into the C5/R5 high radiation areas through HEPA filteration system.
Fire protection is implemented by passive and active means. The passive
method includes internal firewalls, the entire building is subdivided into eight fire
areas by means of firewalls, fire areas include Marshalling Area, Filter/fan Room
1, Filter/Fan Room2, Hot Cells, Filter/Fan Room3, Administrative Area, Analytical
Radiological Laboratories and Maintenance Area. Active fire protection for the entire building is provided by means of sprinkler system.']

Cloud computing strategy

Cloud based productivity and collaboration platform

Integration Platform: Global Market Transaction Processing Hub (GTH)
GTH is light weight Enterprise Service Bus servicing the integration needs of different divisions of State Street. It is built on proven open source stack and supported by Red Hat. The components in the integration hub are JBoss Fuse (Apache Camel, Karaf, Active MQ), JBoss Rules Engine, Quartz for job scheduling, Terracotta Enterprise Cache. It also has custom built components and generic services.

Responsibilities are:

2. Train new teams on using GTH platform.
3. Assist different team in designing and developing their Integration Solution for GTH.
4. Platform upgrade and enhancement with nw components viz JBOSS AMQ7.

BPM Platform
In State Street, different LOBs use and maintain different commercial BPM products for their BPM needs. There was need of unified BPM platform to be used across enterprise for deploying BPM solutions. To address this need, unified BPM platform has been built using "Redhat JBPM" as core. The platform provides the flexibility of using multiple BPM products or use any other BPM product as core. The BPM platform has other features as follows:
1. RESTful API to expose BPM engine.
2. Integrated security mechanism i.e. LDAP for Authentication and ESF (Enterprise Security Framework) for Authorization
3. Customized User group call back.
4. JBPM Work Item handlers for calling any Java class or Web Service.

Responsibilities are:

3. Sample UI in GWT for BPM applications.

Middle Office Reporting Platform
It is reporting platform for which uses Jasper Report templates and State Street's own Cloud Reporting framework to generate the reports periodically. The reports are triggered through Quartz Jobs. A Middleware platform is used to distribute reports via email and SFTP.

Responsibilities are:

The US web-services offer a variety of shared banking functionalities (60+ services) to retail, small-business and commercial customers through multiple channels and applications. The shared services strategy is to build channel/consumer agnostic web-services in a shared fashion. New capabilities/interfaces and new channels/consumers are constantly added/enhanced. SOA Transformation
Participated as team member to define re-engineering strategy for migrating service from different platform to Data Power as part of SOA Transformation initiative. There were over 600 services spread across Message Broker, Java and Mainframe IMS transactions. There services provide different functionalities for different consumers. Project was to define the re-engineering strategy for all the services and migrate it over to suitable ESB platform. In this role, my responsibilities include:
• Document current state (AS-IS) architecture.
• Create the end-to-end high level (TO-BE) architecture for each category of services.
• Implementing services in Data Power using WTX maps for transformation.', u"Solution Architect
Major financial organization - State Street Bank
August 2005 to January 2010
SeeBeyond Decommissioning
State Street Corporation (SSC) took over Investor Bank and Trust (IBT). IBT used SeeBeyond as their Messaging Middleware. The project was to migrate 57 Business interfaces over to Websphere Message Broker. Existing Java code from SeeBeyond for transformation was resused to enable the migration. I was responsible for:
• Designing overall Architect for interface performing transformation to XML.
• Interface Designing for Message Broker.
• Coding of Message flows/ Message Sets.
• Creating Unit Test plans

Investland Migration
With the purchase of Investors Bank & Trust Company (IBT) and subsequent IBT integration effort, State Street Corporation (SSC) is presented with the opportunity to convert legacy IBT customer relationships to State Street systems. The customer relationship in-scope for the InvestLend (IVL) conversion is Confidential Client North America #1 (CCNA1). CCNA1, the largest institutional lender on the street, is largely serviced by the Directed Lending Operations group (DLO) in California for all of their lending activity. In order to support client's lending business, DLO has used IVL for trade capture, enrichment, processing and routing. I was responsible for the following:
• Interface Designing for Message Broker.
• Coding of Message flows/ Message Sets.
• Creating Unit Test plans and System Integration Test plans

SWIFT Hub
It is strategic solution gateway for State Street based on Service Oriented Architecture, for SWIFT traffic. SWIFT Hub intelligently routes internal SWIFT messages to the business units within State Street. In the preceding architecture, there were sub flows for SWIFT transformation and it's distribution. Any change in the SWIFT distribution functionality or addition of new SWIFT standards used to require heavy development activity. With the development of SWIFT Hub, all the transformation and its subsequent distribution to various applications are exposed as services. Any change in SWIFT distribution rule or any addition of new SWIFT standard doesn't need any change in the client specific message flows. Client sets the Meta data values in MQRFH and sends canonical XML to the SWIFT Hub. The Delegation service retrieves the values in metadata and drives the Transformation and distribution service. I was responsible for the following:
• Interface Designing for Message Broker.
• Coding of Message flows/ Message Sets.
• Unit Test plans and System Integration Test plans

MIS Black Box
Black application reconciles the General Ledger data. Black Box requires the data in XML format to do the reconciliation. All Clients of State Street send their data in different formats. MIS also wanted to own the ability to change the transformation rule for the final XML output. MQSI solution to achieve the objective, make use of database to store the Meta data information. Once the data is transformed to Canonical XML, it makes use of XSL files to transform Canonical XML to the required Black Box XML format. XSL files are deployed on the web server which is owned by MIS. It gives them liberty to change the transformation rule. I was responsible for the following:
• Interface Designing for Message Broker.
• Coding of Message flows/ Message Sets.
• Unit Test plans and System Integration Test plans.

European Transfer Agency (ETA)
State Street has built a trading platform for Transfer Agency business out of Ireland and Luxemburg. The platform provides efficient order management and comprehensive, real-time execution of trades for portfolio managers and traders as well as compliance and operations personnel. The trading platform built by AICC offers a comprehensive solution for the confirmation and processing of trade transactions. The Transfer agency platform consists of several interfaces: Dealing Orders: Allows TA to accept orders (15022 Swift MT502(message for Ordering to buy, sell or switch)) sent via Swift Network. Received orders are acknowledged with Swift MT509(message for trade status). Upon pricing and confirmation MT515 (message for trade confirmation) is sent to the clients. Batch Dealing Order: allows Transfer Agency business to accept orders from non-swift clients. This interface supports clients using proprietary formats like RBC Dexia, GFS, Merryl Lynch etc Payments: Provides straight through processing for Transfer Agency payments by sending 15022 Swift MT103 (message for money transfer) and MT202 (message for delivering money) messages. Statements: Monthly/yearly/on-demand holding and transaction statements are sent to the counter-parties via SWIFT network. Swift MT535 and MT536 (messages for Statement of transactions) that support ClearStream and FundSettle formats are generated. Settlements: Transfer agency Settlement instructions are transformed into MT540/541, MT542 /MT543 (messages for settlement instructions) messages and are loaded into State street accounting system. Global Reconciliation Platform: Provides solutions to carry out the reconciliation and life cycle management of all trades that are placed within the funds where State Street is the Transfer agent for and where settlement is expected in the various platforms available for example Clearstream and Euroclear. I was responsible for the following:
• Interface Designing for Message Broker.
• Coding of Message flows/ Message Sets.
• Unit Test plans and System Integration Test plans."]

work_exp:
[u'Senior Systems Architect
Avion Solutions, Inc - Huntsville, AL
June 2000 to Present
Developed an enterprise-level system that will be used to assist in the fielding of small arms for the US Army. The system consists of an ASP.NET MVC 5 web site and an Oracle 12c database that interfaces with Intermec Windows Mobile devices. The mobile devices are used to issue small arms to US Army units by scanning 2-IUID Data matrix marks attached to the items that are being fielded. The scanned data is uploaded to the enterprise Oracle repository and the web site is used to generate XML files that are imported into PBUSE, the US Army's web-based property.

Assisted in the development of INTACT, a Jail Management System. Led the development of interfaces to an external Police Record Management System and the inmate transfer module. Made major enhancements s to the arrest, booking, and release modules. Developed the SOA based biometric and image processing interfaces for the product.

Developed an enterprise-level biometrics system and SDK that uses the Hitachi Finger Vein Reader. The system consists of a client-based C++ COM module that interfaces with a C# .NET web service which calls a multi-threaded server-based C++ dynamic link library. The system provides biometric enrollment, identification, and verification functions. The web service was written in C# and uses the Microsoft.NET Entity Framework to store and maintain biometric information records (BIR) in either Microsoft SQL Server or MySQL databases.

Developed a physical access system using the Hitachi Finger Vein Reader which utilizes the biometric SDK mentioned above. This system uses a service oriented architecture that is comprised of JSON based web services that link the following software components:

• An IOT biometric workstation app that operates electronic locks via software controlled relays
• A workstation based, loosely coupled, data synchronization service
• A server based WebAPI 2.0 data synchronization service
• An ASP.NET MVC based administration web site.

The administrative functions include enrollment, assignment of enrollees to enrollment groups, the assignment of group access rights, open schedules. The web site also allows administrators to unlock and lock down portals from remote locations.

Developed software applications that interface with the DoD Common Access Card (CAC) smart card. These applications include CAC middleware for Windows Mobile device, a Cryptographic Service Provider for Windows Mobile based devices, a .NET Framework and Compact Framework based SDK for the CAC, and a .NET based COM enabled web browser plug-in for the CAC.

Developed an enterprise level system used for tagging DoD parts with a unique identifier as required by the Defense Federal Acquisition Regulation for the reporting of government property in the possession of contractors. The system consists of an ASP.NET Web Forms and ASP.NET MVC web applications, XML web service, Windows Mobile, Android, and Blackberry applications used for tagging DoD parts with a unique identifier as required by the Defense Federal Acquisition Regulation for the reporting of government property in the possession of contractors. This web site accepts XML input from an XML-based web service, which extracts data from the ULLS-A Supply database and produces tags that contain a 2-D data matrix barcode. These tags are permanently affixed to the part and uniquely identify it in the government inventory. The application also sends the required data elements for the to the Defense Federal Acquisition Item Unique Identification (IUID) Registry in the required XML format. C#, VB.NET, JavaScript, AJAX, and JSON were the development languages to develop this system the databases was MS SQL Server 2008 R2.

Led the development and support of the Aviation Maintenance Automated Tracking System (AMATS). AMATS is an automated identification technology system uses contact memory buttons attached to the aircraft components to store historical aircraft component information. Designed a multi-tier web-based system that allows automated aircraft logbook systems to access data stored Macsema contact memory buttons. This included developing application to synchronize database tables that reside in a PocketPC database with a database on a Web server using Active Server Pages through a client-based ActiveX control and JavaScript. Developed software to electronically send component installation, removal and repair information from Army units to AMCOM's Integrated Materiel Management Center. Developed a program that imports component information from Macsema ButtonReader and wireless Symbol 8100 (Pocket PC) handheld computers into the Army's Enhanced Logbook Automation System (ELAS), Unit Level Logistical System - Aviation (ULLS-A E), and the Depot Level Maintenance Database (DLMD). The Macsema ButtonReader hardware is programmed with an embedded C program. The Symbol 8100 is programmed using Microsoft Embedded Visual Basic 3.0. The Windows software is being written in Microsoft Visual Basic 6 using DAO and ADO Microsoft SQL Server, Access, and Oracle databases. Also developed a HTML based help system and wrote user's manuals for the system.

Supporting the Aviation Engineering Directorate's Critical Safety Item System (CSI) website and supporting applications. The CSI system is used to establish policy, procedures, and assigns responsibilities for the life-cycle management of aircraft parts deemed critical to aviation safety as required by the Department of Defense (DoD). Responsibilities include the analysis and evaluation of existing automated and manual systems to support CSI and the development, enhancement, testing, documentation of new and existing CSI software systems. Participated in the design of the Joint Service Critical Safety Item Management Data Viewer. Developed U.S. Army's ASP.NET XML based web service to support the Joint Service Critical Safety Item Management Data Viewer. Developed a report generation system based on SQL Server 2000 Report Services to generate Quality Deficiency Reports (QDR) and distribute them over the web.

Supported the design and development of web-based interface between the Interactive Authoring and Display System (IADS) Aviation Unit Intermediate Maintenance Repair Parts Special Tools List (RPSTL) and the Unit Level Logistical System - Aviation (ULLS-A) SCP6 Supply module. This is a Microsoft ASP.NET based interface which accepts an XML encoded "shopping cart" from the (Repair Parts and Special Tool List (RPSTL) and submits the parts requests contained therein to the ULLS-A SCP6 Supply Module for processing.']

work_exp:
[u"Enterprise Architect
New York City Fire Department - Brooklyn, NY
The Fire Department of the City of New York (FDNY) is the largest Fire Department in the United States and universally is recognized as the world's busiest and most highly skilled emergency response agency, providing fire protection, search and rescue, pre-hospital care and other critical public safety services to residents and visitors in the five boroughs.

Project Details
Oracle Engineered Systems Implementation & Support
Oracle Cloud Implementation & Support
Technology Used: Oracle Exadata X2-2, Oracle Exalogic X3-2, Oracle Database 11gR2, Oracle Fusion Middleware, Oracle Java, DB & Mobile Cloud Services
Details: This was a massive multi-year infrastructure modernization and consolidation program instituted by the the FDNY to replace its ageing SPARC Solaris hardware and old software systems with the next generation technologies. FDNY chose Oracle Engineered Systems - 2 Exadata Systems & 2 Exalogic Systems - as the replacements and I was brought in during the planning phase of the Exalogic implementation to help with the design and deployment of the overall hardware and software infrastructure. I put together a comprehensive design that allowed the FDNY to consolidate over 100 physical servers running several hundreds of different applications into a single Exalogic Quarter Rack. In addition to designing the enterprise, I was responsible for the implementation and deployment of all software componentsa and for supporting the migration of all of their applications and databases to the new engineered systems. As is evident from the technologies listed above, this implementation consisted of the whole gamut of Oracle's Database & Fusion Middleware technologies including Oracle SOA Suite, Oracle Webcenter Suite, Oracle Identity Management Suite, Oracle Business Intelligence Suite, etc. I also undertook the FDNY's public-facing and mobile initiatives and implemented a complete Cloud infrastructure based on Oracle Cloud Services such that FDNY could finally start building public facing apps as well as mobile apps for its largely remote workforce.", u'Enterprise Architect
Godfrey Phillips India - New Delhi, Delhi
Godfrey Phillips India Limited - a part of the larger Modi Group - is one of the largest manufacturers and distributors of tobacco based products in India.

Project Details
Oracle Engineered Systems Implementation & Support
Technology Used: Oracle Exadata X3-2, Oracle Exadata X4-2, Oracle Exalogic X4-2, Oracle Database 11gR2, Oracle Fusion Middleware, Oracle E-Business Suite, PeopleSoft, SAP
Details: This was again a huge multi-year migration and modernization effort undertaken by GPIL. Given that GPIL was a major "Oracle shop" and owned several Oracle hardware & software products, they chose to continue that association and use Oracle Engineered Systems for the migration. The entire effort was a series of large and small projects undertaken to eventually bring all of GPIL's systems on Exadata/Exalogic. I oversaw a fairly large and diverse team of individuals that included Architects, DBAs, Application Administrators, System Administrators & Developers. We started by designing the the end-state architecture for the enterprise and then worked backwords to plan the migration effort. During this migration, several hundred terabytes worth of databases were migrated to Exadata, over 50 COTS (including EBS, PeopleSoft & SAP) & custom applications were migrated to Exalogic, an enterprise-wide Identity Management & Single Sign-on initiative that included integration with AD & Exchange was completed and several new custom applications were developed. This initiative was also the first successful migration of a SAP database to Exadata in all of India.', u"Solutions Architect
Hampton City Schools - Hampton, VA
Hampton City Schools is the administrative body which is responsible for the entire school system within the city of Hampton, Virginia. It is the central organization that manages the entire computer network of the school system including all software - teaching and otherwise.

Project Details
Single Sign-On for Oracle E-Business Suite 11i
Technology Used: Oracle E-Business Suite 11i, Oracle Database 10g, Oracle Discoverer 10g, Oracle Identity Manager, Oracle Internet Directory, Oracle Single Sign-On, SunOne iPlanet LDAP, Microsoft Windows Active Directory, MacSchool Student Information System
Details: The customer was running a host of different software to manage different business and educational processes. Employees with authorized access to different systems had to keep track of a number of different User IDs and Passwords (for example, one for E-Business Suite for viewing their pay slips, one for iPlanet for their email, a separate one for Active Directory to login to the domain, etc.). The customer wanted a single centralized solution that would ensure that all employees would have a single user id and password that they would use to login to all different applications within the School System. The solution of choice was Oracle Identity Manager for the provisioning and OID/SSO for the single master source of truth and single sign-on. I was the solution architect and heading the technical team tasked with integrating all the different applications and bringing them all under the Single Sign-On umbrella. I designed a solution where all new employees that are hired into the organization's HRMS system (Oracle E-Business Suite), will automatically get an account provisioned into the Oracle Internet Directory, E-Business Suite, iPlanet, Active Directory and MacSchool by employing Oracle Identity Manager as the central provisioning system. Any changes to a user's account would be managed centrally via the Oracle Identity Manager and would then automatically get propagated to all other systems. Users wishing to view their payslips or login to Discoverer would be able to do so via a single login page, i.e., the Single Sign-On.

Oracle Identity Management Implementation
Technology Used: Oracle E-Business Suite R12, Oracle Database 11g, Oracle Identity Manager, Oracle Access Manager, Oracle Internet Directory, Microsoft Windows Active Directory, MacSchool Student Information System
Details: This was an upgrade of the previous environment that the customer undertook after running Single Sign-on with Oracle E-Business Suite 11i successfully for almost 4 years. The customer was in the process of upgrading their Oracle Applications environment to R12 and wanted to perform a simultaneous upgrade of their Identity Management environment to the latest 11g version. Both of these activities were undertaken in order to stay under Oracle's current support umbrella as well as to implement additional validations and business processs. Because of the fact that Oracle IdM 11g is a completely different product from the old 10g version, rather than it being an upgrade, this project was a full-blown implementation of a complete identity management system designed to automate all of the customer's needs with respect to user account management and administration.", u'Solutions Architect & Project Lead
ADS Inc - Virginia Beach, VA
Atlantic Diving Supply is a prime-vendor of supplies to the US military and US government. The customer required a CRM system to be built so that ADS can offer a workflow management as a service to its customers and also a full-fledged ERP system to help streamline the company's business processes. The CRM system was required to be highly scalable and customizable to support the extremely different workflow needs of each of ADS' customers. I led the project with a team of 7 developers working in development of a custom application and worked with another team of 10 consultants involved in configuring and deploying Oracle's eBusiness Suite of Applications for ADS. Currently, the entire set of applications is in Maintenance.

Project Details
Special Operations Logistics & Visibility Solution (SOLVS)
Technology Used: Oracle Application Express, Oracle Database 10g, Oracle eBusiness Suite 11i
Details: This is a highly scalable and available CRM system. It allows ADS to provide its customers with a workflow management service for material ordering. It is designed to allow ADS' customers to order material from ADS via a secure & exclusive (to each customer) website and incorporates a sophisticated workflow that allows each customer to customize the application according to its own very specific and unique requirements. Tight integration with Oracle eBusiness Suite allows real-time acceptance of orders by ADS Sales staff and processing, thereby reducing lead time for order fulfillment to a bare minimum. Also provides transparency for the customer by giving up-to-date info on the status of each order.

Quote Management System (QMS)
Technology Used: Oracle Application Express, Oracle Database 10g, Oracle eBusiness Suite 11i
Details: ADS has very special requirements with regards to the way they submit quotes to their customers. A variety of rules and special constraints were required to be in place before ADS sales staff could be allowed to generate quotes. In addition, special workflows including quote value limits, pricing thresholds, etc. were also required. All these reasons prompted the development of a custom Quote Management System that incorporated all these features along with tight integration with Oracle eBusiness Suite. QMS has been integrated right into the heart of the Oracle eBusiness Suite CRM & OM modules and allows Sales staff to convert leads into opportunities (handled by CRM) into quote (handled by QMS) and then finally book a quote into a Sales Order.

Oracle eBusiness Suite Implementation
Technology Used: Oracle eBusiness Suite 11i
Details: Oracle's eBusiness Suite is an industry leading ERP solution that looks at automating all the business processes of a company including HR, Supply Chain Management, Sales Management, Online Sales, Inventory Management, Warehouse Management, Customer Management, Financial Management, etc. GL, AR, AP, CE, INV, WSH, WMS, OM, PO, IBE (iStore), IBC, JTF, CRM modules have been implemented. In addition, custom applications - SOLVS & QMS have been integrated with Apps to provide functionality not available in Apps.

Custom Reporting
Technology Used: Oracle Discoverer 10g, Oracle Database 10g, Oracle eBusiness Suite 11i
Details: ADS had a lot of custom reporting and Business Intelligence Requirements that we fulfilled by implementing Oracle Discoverer 10g. We used the pre-seeded Oracle Apps EUL and added our own customizations to implement the reports and executive dashboards that were required.

Sales Order EDI Interface
Technology Used: Oracle Application Express, Oracle Database 10g, Oracle eBusiness Suite 11i
Details: ADS receives orders from its customers in a variety of ways including phoned in orders, via the ADS website, etc. One of the most important modes of order receipt is EDI data files. Different customers use different formats for the datafiles. The Sales Order EDI Interface is capable of handling all the different and varied formats by allowing the EDI Administrator to train the system in identifying the data received by defining "EDI Sets".']

Currently, the provider data of Anthem Inc. is scattered in 9 legacy provider data management systems. The whole system of legacy provider data management systems is called as Enterprise Provider Data Systems (EPDS v2). Maintaining provider data in several systems lead to many issues as follows:

1. Prohibits improving and streamlining provider data operations.
2. Creates duplicate data.
3. Reduces data veracity and timeliness.
4. Diminishes the provider and member experience.
5. Handicaps business agility.
6. Normalizing and staging nine data sources introduces delays.

Our Project Goal is build a single enterprise-wide provider enablement system which maintains single integrated data platform for all markets and regions to access one shared data set. Provider Business Rules Engine (PBRE) is an application that is built in PEGA using PEGA Declarative network mechanism to execute to contain the business rules. WellCare

Project Description
Utilization management is the evaluation of the appropriateness, medical need and efficiency of health care services procedures and facilities according to established criteria or guidelines and under the provisions of an applicable health benefits plan. Request is approved or denied based on medical necessity. Denials would also include criteria reviewed, opportunity for a peer to peer discussion and appeal rights. It is also determined under UM that where patient should go after discharge from hospital. For example, if patient needs to go to nursing facility, or rehabilitation is required, or patient should go on case management for chronic disease. UM ensures that member receives the right care, at the right place, and at the right time. In WellCare UM process includes following steps:

Provider submit their request via fax, phone, mail or web (Provider Portal).
Request was reviewed by initial team to determine if authorization is required.
If review/authorization is required, then authorization request is forwarded to the UM team for processing.
Clinical user reviews the authorization case and approves if he/she thinks that it meets criteria.
In WellCare Clinical users cannot deny any authorization so if they think that criteria is not met they send authorization request to Medical Director for further review.
If Medical Director thinks that the authorization should be denied, he/she denies it.
If case is denied, member has the opportunity to appeal for it.
All this process is implemented in Pega platform.', u'Sr. System Architect
